1
00:00:10,297 --> 00:00:11,587
Thank you, New York.

2
00:00:11,588 --> 00:00:14,171
<i>It's humbling to be speaking to you
as Mayor.</i>

3
00:00:14,172 --> 00:00:18,754
[Sheila] Vanessa's resistance
is hurting you with traditional voters.

4
00:00:18,755 --> 00:00:21,962
[Fisk] <i>My wife and I, we have work to do.</i>

5
00:00:21,963 --> 00:00:26,296
[Buck] Dr. Glenn, allow me to introduce
Mayor and Mrs. Fisk.

6
00:00:26,297 --> 00:00:28,629
Hector Ayala?
You know, they're saying you killed a cop?

7
00:00:28,630 --> 00:00:30,629
[Hector] <i>Look, I didn't push him, I swear.</i>

8
00:00:30,630 --> 00:00:32,046
[Matt] <i>I'd still like to represent you.</i>

9
00:00:32,047 --> 00:00:33,712
Hector, he's not the man I married.

10
00:00:33,713 --> 00:00:34,796
[Matt] <i>White Tiger?</i>

11
00:00:34,797 --> 00:00:35,879
<i>You neglect to tell me</i>

12
00:00:35,880 --> 00:00:38,754
- that you moonlight as a vigilante?
- Someone's gotta protect the streets.

13
00:00:38,755 --> 00:00:41,462
I need you to find the witness
that Hector saved on the platform.

14
00:00:41,463 --> 00:00:42,754
[knock on door]

15
00:00:42,755 --> 00:00:44,754
[Matt] <i>Nicky. You're the only person
standing between</i>

16
00:00:44,755 --> 00:00:46,296
<i>Hector and consecutive life sentences.</i>

17
00:00:46,297 --> 00:00:47,587
Where is he?

18
00:00:47,588 --> 00:00:49,172
Sadly, he's no longer here.

19
00:00:50,755 --> 00:00:51,921
You don't want to do this.

20
00:00:51,922 --> 00:00:53,755
[grunting]

21
00:00:56,047 --> 00:00:57,047
[screaming]

22
00:01:00,255 --> 00:01:01,379
[keys jingling]

23
00:01:01,380 --> 00:01:02,838
- [buzzer sounds]
- [door unlocks]

24
00:01:04,672 --> 00:01:05,672
[Matt] Thanks.

25
00:01:07,380 --> 00:01:08,380
[creaking]

26
00:01:09,713 --> 00:01:10,797
[lock clicking]

27
00:01:11,547 --> 00:01:13,672
They, uh, bring you some food?

28
00:01:15,672 --> 00:01:16,672
No.

29
00:01:23,255 --> 00:01:24,505
[Hector breathes deeply]

30
00:01:26,588 --> 00:01:29,588
Luquillo is a beach
near where I'm from in Puerto Rico.

31
00:01:30,672 --> 00:01:33,087
To me,
it's the most beautiful place on Earth.

32
00:01:33,088 --> 00:01:38,297
White sand, palm trees, and the coquis.

33
00:01:39,255 --> 00:01:40,505
It's a little tree frog.

34
00:01:41,422 --> 00:01:43,588
Doesn't croak. It sings its name.

35
00:01:44,172 --> 00:01:45,213
[whistling coqui's call]

36
00:01:49,963 --> 00:01:53,296
[laughs] I laugh
because the tourists, man,

37
00:01:53,297 --> 00:01:56,047
they think it's noisy and annoying,

38
00:01:57,088 --> 00:02:00,629
but to us <i>boricuas,</i>
man, it's a magical sound.

39
00:02:00,630 --> 00:02:02,130
[♪ mellow music playing]

40
00:02:02,713 --> 00:02:07,255
And the coqui, it mates for life, right?
So, every sunset...

41
00:02:10,588 --> 00:02:15,588
thousands of these frogs start calling out
to their one and only love.

42
00:02:19,838 --> 00:02:21,088
It's the music of the island.

43
00:02:23,880 --> 00:02:26,672
You're gonna see that beach again, Hector.
I promise.

44
00:02:27,713 --> 00:02:30,130
And you'll be reunited with your family.

45
00:02:33,880 --> 00:02:34,880
[exhales sharply]

46
00:02:35,338 --> 00:02:37,338
[♪ theme music playing]

47
00:04:15,130 --> 00:04:17,755
[ship horn bellows]

48
00:04:23,588 --> 00:04:25,588
[engine revving]

49
00:04:39,297 --> 00:04:40,297
[passenger] Yo, what's up?

50
00:04:43,047 --> 00:04:46,046
- Be cool. It's a gimme.
- [engine stops]

51
00:04:46,047 --> 00:04:47,547
No one plays cowboy.

52
00:04:48,172 --> 00:04:49,380
[exhales softly]

53
00:04:54,463 --> 00:04:56,547
[sniffles] Evenin', gentlemen.

54
00:04:57,047 --> 00:04:58,922
Whoo! Nippy, isn't it?

55
00:04:59,630 --> 00:05:00,630
[Devlin chuckles]

56
00:05:01,130 --> 00:05:04,421
I couldn't trouble you for the keys
to this fine vehicle, could I?

57
00:05:04,422 --> 00:05:06,337
- Here you go.
- Thank you very much.

58
00:05:06,338 --> 00:05:09,755
And, uh... wallets, while you're at it.

59
00:05:14,963 --> 00:05:16,338
- Here you go.
- Thank you.

60
00:05:19,963 --> 00:05:21,171
You too, Susan.

61
00:05:21,172 --> 00:05:22,962
Do you know whose truck this is?

62
00:05:22,963 --> 00:05:24,047
Oh.

63
00:05:25,130 --> 00:05:26,505
Are you a hard man, are ya?

64
00:05:27,255 --> 00:05:28,463
Yeah.

65
00:05:30,172 --> 00:05:31,547
Silly wee bastard.

66
00:05:32,963 --> 00:05:34,172
[gun fires]

67
00:05:35,255 --> 00:05:37,005
[gasps, chuckles]

68
00:05:37,963 --> 00:05:39,172
[gun fires]

69
00:05:40,672 --> 00:05:41,880
{\an8}[♪ upbeat music playing,
Salvi "Mi Canto"]

70
00:05:42,338 --> 00:05:45,754
{\an8}I look over my shoulder, but I grew up
in the city. I'm not afraid,

71
00:05:45,755 --> 00:05:47,879
{\an8}<i>but somebody invades my privacy,</i>

72
00:05:47,880 --> 00:05:52,296
{\an8}I have no problem taking my piece
and putting it to their head. That's it.

73
00:05:52,297 --> 00:05:54,796
{\an8}[man] <i>Long, dark nights out here, man.</i>

74
00:05:54,797 --> 00:05:58,296
{\an8}Good versus evil, evil versus evil,
good versus good.

75
00:05:58,297 --> 00:06:00,962
{\an8}<i>Is New York gonna make it? I don't know.</i>

76
00:06:00,963 --> 00:06:03,505
{\an8}<i>You want answers from me?
I don't have 'em, sorry.</i>

77
00:06:06,880 --> 00:06:08,505
[♪ music continues muffled]

78
00:06:24,797 --> 00:06:28,713
I hear Bacon's Freud triptych
is coming up for auction... again.

79
00:06:31,130 --> 00:06:32,255
The yellow one.

80
00:06:34,588 --> 00:06:35,838
You remember.

81
00:06:37,088 --> 00:06:38,130
I remember.

82
00:06:39,797 --> 00:06:42,797
I could wash two hundred million
through that sale.

83
00:06:43,713 --> 00:06:47,546
I know that it hurts to just sit by,

84
00:06:47,547 --> 00:06:50,838
but I'm reaching for higher goals.

85
00:06:53,130 --> 00:06:54,129
Such as?

86
00:06:54,130 --> 00:06:55,212
[knock on door]

87
00:06:55,213 --> 00:06:57,421
[Sheila] Sorry to bother you, sir,

88
00:06:57,422 --> 00:07:01,421
but you wanted to be updated on anything
happening near the Red Hook Port.

89
00:07:01,422 --> 00:07:02,546
- [Fisk] Yes.
- [Sheila] Yeah.

90
00:07:02,547 --> 00:07:05,921
Last night, there was a double homicide
not half a mile from the port.

91
00:07:05,922 --> 00:07:08,629
Apparently, a hijacking gone wrong.

92
00:07:08,630 --> 00:07:12,504
It really doesn't help
sell the place as a destination.

93
00:07:12,505 --> 00:07:15,338
We should make the appropriate calls...

94
00:07:16,213 --> 00:07:20,630
and inspire Chief Gallo
to make it a priority.

95
00:07:22,880 --> 00:07:24,047
Yeah, we can try.

96
00:07:27,338 --> 00:07:28,338
[footsteps recede]

97
00:07:29,088 --> 00:07:32,879
[Vanessa] They're misbehaving because
there's no one at the head of the table.

98
00:07:32,880 --> 00:07:37,630
Without you or me there,
they'll turn on each other.

99
00:07:39,047 --> 00:07:40,422
They're rats.

100
00:07:41,588 --> 00:07:45,379
Rats at the bottom of the barrel.
Let them kill each other.

101
00:07:45,380 --> 00:07:48,587
[Vanessa] And when
they're done with each other,

102
00:07:48,588 --> 00:07:51,047
whoever is left standing
will come after you.

103
00:07:55,547 --> 00:08:01,880
That world, that kind of violence,
petty blood feuds...

104
00:08:05,922 --> 00:08:07,254
None of it is our concern.

105
00:08:07,255 --> 00:08:08,547
[footsteps approaching]

106
00:08:13,797 --> 00:08:15,797
[chorus vocalizing]

107
00:08:48,672 --> 00:08:50,046
[sighs]

108
00:08:50,047 --> 00:08:52,755
[Powell, echoing] Yeah, okay.
I'll be right there.

109
00:08:54,422 --> 00:08:55,463
[door opens]

110
00:08:58,838 --> 00:09:01,129
You know, you don't need
those glasses indoors, right?

111
00:09:01,130 --> 00:09:03,379
[sputters] I'm sorry,
are you talking to me?

112
00:09:03,380 --> 00:09:04,505
Who's there?

113
00:09:05,797 --> 00:09:07,421
[♪ uneasy music playing]

114
00:09:07,422 --> 00:09:09,547
So, you're a blind lawyer who can fight.

115
00:09:10,630 --> 00:09:11,630
Ah.

116
00:09:12,172 --> 00:09:13,213
Officer Powell.

117
00:09:16,713 --> 00:09:19,212
You know, Murdock, I bet Judge Cooper
would be interested to hear

118
00:09:19,213 --> 00:09:21,337
that you're interfering
with a police investigation.

119
00:09:21,338 --> 00:09:22,837
Oh, I think you mean a shakedown.

120
00:09:22,838 --> 00:09:26,172
It doesn't exactly seem ethical.
I bet he'd throw you right off the case.

121
00:09:26,963 --> 00:09:28,546
Well, at least I won't go to jail.

122
00:09:28,547 --> 00:09:30,379
Witness tampering is a serious offense.

123
00:09:30,380 --> 00:09:33,338
Now, maybe you get lucky, and the DA only
slaps you with a misdemeanor...

124
00:09:33,963 --> 00:09:34,963
but I doubt it.

125
00:09:38,297 --> 00:09:39,880
I'll see you in court, Officer.

126
00:09:42,838 --> 00:09:44,755
[♪ heavy metal music playing
over speakers, Slayer "Crionics"]

127
00:10:01,213 --> 00:10:05,047
I think you've misunderstood
the concept of a safe house.

128
00:10:05,422 --> 00:10:07,254
Probably got eyes on us.

129
00:10:07,255 --> 00:10:09,338
He says it relaxes him or whatever.

130
00:10:10,380 --> 00:10:11,630
That's what this is for.

131
00:10:12,255 --> 00:10:16,838
Hey! Cherry Cola,
you're back, man. Finally.

132
00:10:19,547 --> 00:10:22,837
This is it? Come on, man.

133
00:10:22,838 --> 00:10:26,046
First of all, it's not a party.
I'm not your man.

134
00:10:26,047 --> 00:10:29,212
And this is just for me to get you
on the stand without sweating and puking.

135
00:10:29,213 --> 00:10:32,255
Relax. I got you. Hey.

136
00:10:39,130 --> 00:10:42,879
For how long have you been with the NYPD,
Officer Powell?

137
00:10:42,880 --> 00:10:44,213
Uh, just over 15 years.

138
00:10:44,963 --> 00:10:46,171
[Hochberg] And in those 15 years,

139
00:10:46,172 --> 00:10:49,754
how many commendations of excellence
have you received?

140
00:10:49,755 --> 00:10:53,047
[Powell] Three. I got one for integrity
and two for community service.

141
00:10:53,797 --> 00:10:57,546
[Hochberg] Would you say it was unusual
for an officer of your seniority

142
00:10:57,547 --> 00:10:59,212
to be working on New Year's Eve?

143
00:10:59,213 --> 00:11:01,129
[Powell] Well, I volunteered.

144
00:11:01,130 --> 00:11:04,837
Well, a lotta the guys in my precinct,
they got families, you know, kids,

145
00:11:04,838 --> 00:11:07,254
and mine are grown. Kel's too.

146
00:11:07,255 --> 00:11:10,587
Kel, Officer Shanahan, your partner?

147
00:11:10,588 --> 00:11:13,462
Yeah. We were assigned
to Washington Heights,

148
00:11:13,463 --> 00:11:16,212
and lotta the guys got sent down
to Times Square for the ball drop.

149
00:11:16,213 --> 00:11:20,087
Did you and Officer Shanahan
see much action that night?

150
00:11:20,088 --> 00:11:22,046
[Powell] We didn't see any action

151
00:11:22,047 --> 00:11:24,546
until we got down
to the platform on 168th.

152
00:11:24,547 --> 00:11:26,588
[Hochberg] Hm. What happened there?

153
00:11:27,380 --> 00:11:29,837
[Powell] Well, we were just finishing up
a routine sweep.

154
00:11:29,838 --> 00:11:31,880
You know, the place was like a ghost town,

155
00:11:32,005 --> 00:11:34,587
and... uh, the defendant,
he just came outta nowhere.

156
00:11:34,588 --> 00:11:37,296
He had this wild look in his eyes,
and when you're a cop long enough,

157
00:11:37,297 --> 00:11:40,296
you know what that look means,
and he starts running toward us.

158
00:11:40,297 --> 00:11:41,380
[inhales sharply]

159
00:11:42,422 --> 00:11:44,504
[Hochberg, echoing] Did you tell
the defendant to stop?

160
00:11:44,505 --> 00:11:45,712
[heartbeat thumping]

161
00:11:45,713 --> 00:11:47,047
[Powell, echoing] Yes, many times.

162
00:11:49,380 --> 00:11:50,672
[softly] Don't react, Hector.

163
00:11:52,713 --> 00:11:54,504
[Powell] We yelled and flashed our badges,

164
00:11:54,505 --> 00:11:57,087
but he just kept on coming.
He starts pounding on us, and then...

165
00:11:57,088 --> 00:11:59,380
I feel Kel pull him off me.

166
00:12:00,130 --> 00:12:03,505
Next thing I know, the guy just takes Kel
and pushes him in front of the train.

167
00:12:06,172 --> 00:12:07,172
Like it was nothin'.

168
00:12:07,922 --> 00:12:09,087
[Hochberg] Like it was nothing?

169
00:12:09,088 --> 00:12:10,671
Objection. Leading.

170
00:12:10,672 --> 00:12:12,588
- [Judge Cooper] Sustained.
- [Hochberg exhales]

171
00:12:15,047 --> 00:12:19,047
[Hochberg] Officer Powell,
I know how hard this is for you.

172
00:12:19,713 --> 00:12:22,838
Me and Kel Shanahan,
we were partners for eight years.

173
00:12:23,630 --> 00:12:27,087
You know,
that's eight years of beers and kids,

174
00:12:27,088 --> 00:12:29,421
and just talking about how shitty
the Knicks are.

175
00:12:29,422 --> 00:12:30,547
[chuckles softly]

176
00:12:31,547 --> 00:12:33,797
Kel Shanahan was my best friend.

177
00:12:35,172 --> 00:12:36,672
And that's all over now.

178
00:12:38,755 --> 00:12:40,212
[Hochberg] No further questions.

179
00:12:40,213 --> 00:12:42,297
[♪ uneasy music playing]

180
00:12:46,963 --> 00:12:48,422
Officer Powell, good morning, um...

181
00:12:49,005 --> 00:12:50,504
I'm told you have a black eye.

182
00:12:50,505 --> 00:12:52,921
- I hope everything is okay.
- Yeah, don't worry about it.

183
00:12:52,922 --> 00:12:55,046
You know,
there's this thing they say in boxing.

184
00:12:55,047 --> 00:12:57,421
The best cure for a black eye
is fast hands.

185
00:12:57,422 --> 00:12:58,837
- Objection.
- [Judge Cooper] Sustained.

186
00:12:58,838 --> 00:13:00,629
Come on, Mr. Murdock.

187
00:13:00,630 --> 00:13:03,171
[Matt] Officer Powell, I just wanna
make sure I'm clear on something.

188
00:13:03,172 --> 00:13:05,879
You testified that
before my client arrived at the station,

189
00:13:05,880 --> 00:13:07,297
the place was a ghost town.

190
00:13:08,172 --> 00:13:09,171
Yeah.

191
00:13:09,172 --> 00:13:11,879
[Matt] Meaning you and your partner
were alone on the platform.

192
00:13:11,880 --> 00:13:13,129
[Powell] Yes.

193
00:13:13,130 --> 00:13:14,754
[Matt] Now,
language can be strange sometimes

194
00:13:14,755 --> 00:13:16,837
so I just want to make sure
we're saying the same thing here.

195
00:13:16,838 --> 00:13:19,754
By "alone," you mean
just the two of you, no one else?

196
00:13:19,755 --> 00:13:22,462
- [Powell] That's right.
- There's no passenger waiting for a train?

197
00:13:22,463 --> 00:13:23,630
No.

198
00:13:24,838 --> 00:13:26,838
No busker playing a guitar?

199
00:13:27,713 --> 00:13:30,212
- No.
- [Matt] Okay. So you're alone.

200
00:13:30,213 --> 00:13:31,505
No buskers or passengers.

201
00:13:32,463 --> 00:13:35,421
Which means there certainly wasn't
a confidential informant

202
00:13:35,422 --> 00:13:36,879
- you were roughing up.
- Objection!

203
00:13:36,880 --> 00:13:39,504
[Judge Cooper] You better have
a good faith basis for this, Mr. Murdock.

204
00:13:39,505 --> 00:13:40,671
[Matt] Yeah, I do, Your Honor.

205
00:13:40,672 --> 00:13:42,712
[Judge Cooper] Tight leash,
if you get my meaning.

206
00:13:42,713 --> 00:13:45,880
Officer Powell, let's try this.
You ever met a man named Nicky Torres?

207
00:13:51,838 --> 00:13:53,129
I never heard of him.

208
00:13:53,130 --> 00:13:56,837
That's curious, 'cause as I understand it,
Nicky Torres is a confidential informant

209
00:13:56,838 --> 00:13:58,212
who used to work with the NYPD.

210
00:13:58,213 --> 00:14:01,505
In fact, he used to work with you
and Officer Shanahan directly.

211
00:14:03,922 --> 00:14:06,462
Officer Powell,
did you and Officer Shanahan

212
00:14:06,463 --> 00:14:09,672
have an arranged meeting with Nicky Torres
on the platform that night?

213
00:14:17,963 --> 00:14:19,422
I told you, I don't know him.

214
00:14:20,922 --> 00:14:22,338
Yeah. You did say that.

215
00:14:24,255 --> 00:14:25,380
Thank you.

216
00:14:30,713 --> 00:14:32,588
[echoes] Torres cannot testify.

217
00:14:47,505 --> 00:14:48,672
[Forrest] He's almost ready.

218
00:14:49,380 --> 00:14:51,837
- What's he doin'?
- Should I be worried?

219
00:14:51,838 --> 00:14:52,963
[Cherry] Yep.

220
00:14:53,505 --> 00:14:55,087
Hey, you promised I'd be safe.

221
00:14:55,088 --> 00:14:57,504
You'll be fine if you stay out of sight.
Come on, let's go.

222
00:14:57,505 --> 00:14:58,838
[♪ tense music playing]

223
00:15:14,005 --> 00:15:16,505
Looking at the doors
isn't gonna get them here any faster.

224
00:15:17,380 --> 00:15:19,088
Who says I'm looking at the doors?

225
00:15:19,713 --> 00:15:21,213
They'll be here.

226
00:15:23,505 --> 00:15:24,505
[engine revving]

227
00:15:36,130 --> 00:15:37,379
[court officer] All rise.

228
00:15:37,380 --> 00:15:40,837
Supreme Court State of New York,
part 20 is in session.

229
00:15:40,838 --> 00:15:43,255
The Honorable Fitzgerald Cooper presiding.

230
00:15:56,838 --> 00:15:58,463
[handcuffs clinking]

231
00:16:00,088 --> 00:16:01,130
[sighs]

232
00:16:01,838 --> 00:16:04,130
- You good?
- Yeah.

233
00:16:08,547 --> 00:16:09,547
[tires screeching]

234
00:16:19,797 --> 00:16:21,005
[siren blaring]

235
00:16:24,713 --> 00:16:26,505
Mr. Murdock, call your witness.

236
00:16:28,797 --> 00:16:31,713
Just another second, Your Honor.

237
00:16:37,338 --> 00:16:38,337
Mornin', Officer.

238
00:16:38,338 --> 00:16:39,797
Get outta the van, asshole.

239
00:16:42,005 --> 00:16:43,088
[softly] Where is he?

240
00:16:46,130 --> 00:16:47,130
Open it.

241
00:16:55,588 --> 00:16:56,796
- [Forrest] You good?
- Yeah.

242
00:16:56,797 --> 00:16:58,005
[Forrest] Come on! Let's go!

243
00:16:59,713 --> 00:17:00,713
[door opens]

244
00:17:03,422 --> 00:17:04,630
- They're here.
- [Matt sighs]

245
00:17:12,255 --> 00:17:13,588
Impeccable timing, buddy.

246
00:17:20,797 --> 00:17:22,796
Would you state your name for the record?

247
00:17:22,797 --> 00:17:25,463
Yeah. My name's Nicky Torres.

248
00:17:26,130 --> 00:17:27,838
[Matt] And, uh, where do you live,
Mr. Torres?

249
00:17:28,755 --> 00:17:29,880
[Torres] Washington Heights.

250
00:17:30,713 --> 00:17:33,047
So, are you close
to the 168th Street subway station?

251
00:17:33,630 --> 00:17:35,547
[Torres] Yeah,
it's four blocks from my house.

252
00:17:36,297 --> 00:17:37,797
[Matt] Where're you working right now?

253
00:17:38,547 --> 00:17:41,129
I'm between jobs at the moment.

254
00:17:41,130 --> 00:17:43,547
Right, you've had a rough
couple of years, huh?

255
00:17:44,422 --> 00:17:46,755
[Torres] Eighteen months ago,
I got pinched for dealing.

256
00:17:47,547 --> 00:17:51,213
I knew I shouldn't have done it,
but I got a kid. I needed money.

257
00:17:51,880 --> 00:17:54,255
[Matt] So, you were looking
at a prison sentence.

258
00:17:54,922 --> 00:17:56,963
What happened with that case?

259
00:17:58,297 --> 00:17:59,754
It went away.

260
00:17:59,755 --> 00:18:01,380
[Matt] Can you tell the jury why?

261
00:18:03,005 --> 00:18:06,088
[Torres] I told the cops
I'd help 'em out sometimes.

262
00:18:06,963 --> 00:18:10,630
[Matt] And by "help out," you mean
become a confidential informant?

263
00:18:12,213 --> 00:18:13,213
Yeah.

264
00:18:14,047 --> 00:18:17,171
Mr. Torres, is that what you were doing
on the night of New Year's Eve?

265
00:18:17,172 --> 00:18:20,588
Were you passing along information
to Officers Shanahan and Powell?

266
00:18:21,547 --> 00:18:23,797
[♪ tense music playing]

267
00:18:30,630 --> 00:18:32,338
[heart thumping]

268
00:18:33,963 --> 00:18:35,463
Remembering you're under oath.

269
00:18:39,672 --> 00:18:41,838
No. I was home all night.

270
00:18:43,922 --> 00:18:45,296
[Matt] Forgive me, I'm confused here.

271
00:18:45,297 --> 00:18:47,004
Previously, you stated pretty clearly that

272
00:18:47,005 --> 00:18:49,462
you were actually at the 168th Street
subway station being beaten

273
00:18:49,463 --> 00:18:51,212
- when Hector Ayala saved your life.
- Objection.

274
00:18:51,213 --> 00:18:52,379
- Objection!
- [Judge Cooper] Sustained.

275
00:18:52,380 --> 00:18:54,004
He put himself in harm's way, didn't he?

276
00:18:54,005 --> 00:18:55,963
- [Kirsten] Matt! Matt!
- [Judge Cooper] Counsel, stand down!

277
00:18:59,213 --> 00:19:01,047
[scattered murmuring]

278
00:19:03,588 --> 00:19:05,463
[exhales sharply] Well, this is bullshit.

279
00:19:06,338 --> 00:19:08,672
- [softly] Just end it.
- Well, what's it gonna be, Mr. Murdock?

280
00:19:09,838 --> 00:19:11,380
I withdraw the witness, Your Honor.

281
00:19:12,880 --> 00:19:14,797
[Judge Cooper]
Mr. Torres, you are dismissed.

282
00:19:15,547 --> 00:19:16,755
[scattered murmuring]

283
00:19:18,755 --> 00:19:20,755
[♪ tense music continues]

284
00:19:46,005 --> 00:19:47,796
The mayor's 30 minutes late.

285
00:19:47,797 --> 00:19:49,296
He won't be joining us.

286
00:19:49,297 --> 00:19:51,879
Now, the shootout two days ago at the port

287
00:19:51,880 --> 00:19:54,797
is just the latest in a long line
of very noisy mistakes.

288
00:19:55,672 --> 00:19:59,879
Truck hijackings, violence at the docks,
a gang war...

289
00:19:59,880 --> 00:20:03,129
These are the headlines splashed across
the front page of <i>The Examiner.</i>

290
00:20:03,130 --> 00:20:04,713
It all ends today.

291
00:20:05,338 --> 00:20:07,880
We don't take orders from you, son.
That's not how things work.

292
00:20:08,755 --> 00:20:10,255
Luca.

293
00:20:11,672 --> 00:20:13,672
This is what you owe Viktor.

294
00:20:15,338 --> 00:20:16,422
Restitution.

295
00:20:22,755 --> 00:20:25,421
1.8. I like the sound of that.

296
00:20:25,422 --> 00:20:27,171
Are you out of your mind?

297
00:20:27,172 --> 00:20:29,046
Maybe next time, hire guys
who know how to jack a truck!

298
00:20:29,047 --> 00:20:30,962
Maybe you shouldn't have hired
a bunch of trigger-happy assholes.

299
00:20:30,963 --> 00:20:33,004
Enough! You're proving my point.

300
00:20:33,005 --> 00:20:37,504
All this arguing, bloodshed, chaos...
It's getting in the way.

301
00:20:37,505 --> 00:20:40,338
1.8. That's the number.

302
00:20:41,797 --> 00:20:43,629
Oh, yeah? I got a better idea.

303
00:20:43,630 --> 00:20:46,421
How about I pay zero dollars to Viktor,
and you go tell Fisk

304
00:20:46,422 --> 00:20:49,087
if he's got something to say to me,
he can come tell me himself?

305
00:20:49,088 --> 00:20:51,588
I don't take orders
from the mayor's errand boy!

306
00:20:53,463 --> 00:20:57,297
I don't work for the mayor.
I work for the man.

307
00:21:00,505 --> 00:21:02,462
[Kirsten] So he was fine
when we prepped him.

308
00:21:02,463 --> 00:21:04,712
He's an annoying pain in the ass,
but he was fine.

309
00:21:04,713 --> 00:21:06,046
So what the hell happened?

310
00:21:06,047 --> 00:21:09,212
Maybe the cops got to him,
or they threatened his kid.

311
00:21:09,213 --> 00:21:11,962
Or he was never on our side
in the first place.

312
00:21:11,963 --> 00:21:13,921
[Cherry] So what do we have without Nicky?

313
00:21:13,922 --> 00:21:17,671
[Matt] Nothing. Our entire defense
just got flushed down the toilet.

314
00:21:17,672 --> 00:21:18,755
[sighs deeply]

315
00:21:19,422 --> 00:21:21,087
[Kirsten] Maybe there's a paper trail,

316
00:21:21,088 --> 00:21:27,129
some kind of CI registration form
or a record of payments or something?

317
00:21:27,130 --> 00:21:29,462
We get that, we can recall him
as a hostile witness.

318
00:21:29,463 --> 00:21:31,921
I looked. There's nothin'.

319
00:21:31,922 --> 00:21:34,712
Powell did everything cash,
kept it all off the books.

320
00:21:34,713 --> 00:21:36,004
He testify for them?

321
00:21:36,005 --> 00:21:38,838
- Is there a case we can hang on him?
- [Cherry] Nothing I found.

322
00:21:39,797 --> 00:21:41,755
He's innocent. We put him on the stand.

323
00:21:42,880 --> 00:21:45,338
He tells his side of the story. The truth.

324
00:21:46,713 --> 00:21:49,422
And we hope the jury see him
the way we do.

325
00:21:51,672 --> 00:21:52,755
It's our only move.

326
00:21:54,380 --> 00:21:56,213
We're gonna need a lot more bourbon.

327
00:21:57,047 --> 00:21:58,088
[bottle opens]

328
00:22:03,088 --> 00:22:05,672
[Fisk] What you're trying to do,
it's not going to work.

329
00:22:07,047 --> 00:22:08,047
Counseling?

330
00:22:12,880 --> 00:22:13,922
Tell me.

331
00:22:19,338 --> 00:22:20,338
[clicks tongue]

332
00:22:21,088 --> 00:22:22,796
I sent Buck to Luca

333
00:22:22,797 --> 00:22:26,713
to tell him to pay Viktor
1.8 restitution for the hijacking.

334
00:22:29,380 --> 00:22:31,963
Let's not fall into a place
where I don't trust you.

335
00:22:37,630 --> 00:22:38,672
[Vanessa sighs]

336
00:22:39,380 --> 00:22:41,713
I don't like watching
everything fall apart.

337
00:22:45,380 --> 00:22:48,213
I respect that.
You wanted to keep the peace.

338
00:22:50,172 --> 00:22:52,672
Sometimes, peace needs to be broken,

339
00:22:53,505 --> 00:22:55,713
and chaos must reign,

340
00:22:56,338 --> 00:22:59,880
just for a moment,
to build a stronger order.

341
00:23:00,505 --> 00:23:03,879
Is that what it is?
Chaos before a stronger peace?

342
00:23:03,880 --> 00:23:06,046
Or is it my penance? For what I did.

343
00:23:06,047 --> 00:23:08,379
- No.
- You're punishing me for Adam.

344
00:23:08,380 --> 00:23:11,213
- I'm not punishing you for anything!
- You're leaving me out in the cold.

345
00:23:18,255 --> 00:23:19,755
Thank you for your patience.

346
00:23:20,922 --> 00:23:23,546
Now, where were we?

347
00:23:23,547 --> 00:23:25,630
[♪ dramatic music playing]

348
00:23:33,338 --> 00:23:36,672
Mr. Ayala, how often would you say
you're at the 168th Street subway station?

349
00:23:37,380 --> 00:23:40,087
A few times a week.
It's close to the apartment.

350
00:23:40,088 --> 00:23:41,629
[Matt] Were you there on New Year's Eve?

351
00:23:41,630 --> 00:23:42,796
Yes.

352
00:23:42,797 --> 00:23:45,213
[Matt] Would you mind walking us through
what happened that night?

353
00:23:45,797 --> 00:23:49,171
[Hector] Yeah, I bought
some flowers at <i>la bodega,</i>

354
00:23:49,172 --> 00:23:51,629
and I was heading down to the station.

355
00:23:51,630 --> 00:23:53,338
[Matt] Where were you going, Mr. Ayala?

356
00:23:56,338 --> 00:23:57,462
[Hector sniffles]

357
00:23:57,463 --> 00:23:58,879
[Matt] Mr. Ayala?

358
00:23:58,880 --> 00:24:04,547
My wife and I,
we, uh, live with my sister and my niece.

359
00:24:05,630 --> 00:24:08,046
Soledad and I, we've always dreamt
of having our own place,

360
00:24:08,047 --> 00:24:11,213
and I had finally saved up the money.

361
00:24:12,880 --> 00:24:16,755
I put a deposit down on a studio
in the South Bronx.

362
00:24:17,505 --> 00:24:20,880
It's not much, but it's ours.

363
00:24:21,838 --> 00:24:25,129
I was going there
to put the flowers there for the next day.

364
00:24:25,130 --> 00:24:27,505
'Cause you wanted to surprise your wife.

365
00:24:28,505 --> 00:24:30,004
- Yes.
- [Matt chuckles softly]

366
00:24:30,005 --> 00:24:33,504
[Matt] Okay, so,
you were heading into the station.

367
00:24:33,505 --> 00:24:34,588
What happens next?

368
00:24:35,338 --> 00:24:36,337
[Hector] I heard yelling.

369
00:24:36,338 --> 00:24:38,713
Sounded like someone
was in trouble, so I ran down...

370
00:24:39,380 --> 00:24:40,630
to see what was going on.

371
00:24:41,213 --> 00:24:42,213
[Matt] What did you see?

372
00:24:42,797 --> 00:24:44,296
[Hector] A man getting beat up.

373
00:24:44,297 --> 00:24:45,837
Did you know the man?

374
00:24:45,838 --> 00:24:48,796
No. And I never saw him again
until yesterday in court.

375
00:24:48,797 --> 00:24:50,671
And now I know his name is Nicky Torres.

376
00:24:50,672 --> 00:24:51,963
[scattered murmuring]

377
00:24:53,380 --> 00:24:55,254
[Matt] What about the men
who were doing the beating?

378
00:24:55,255 --> 00:24:57,171
- Did you know them?
- [Hector] No.

379
00:24:57,172 --> 00:25:00,047
[Matt] Did you know
they were police officers?

380
00:25:00,630 --> 00:25:04,546
No. No, I yelled at them to stop
and they didn't.

381
00:25:04,547 --> 00:25:06,421
So I ran down to help.

382
00:25:06,422 --> 00:25:08,379
And then,
everything just happened so fast.

383
00:25:08,380 --> 00:25:10,921
I tried to break it up,
then they started beating on me,

384
00:25:10,922 --> 00:25:12,129
and I tried to fight them off

385
00:25:12,130 --> 00:25:14,963
and then, all of a sudden, one of them
slipped and fell onto the tracks.

386
00:25:17,213 --> 00:25:18,338
I was just trying to help.

387
00:25:19,172 --> 00:25:21,254
I didn't want anyone to get hurt.

388
00:25:21,255 --> 00:25:22,588
[Matt] Could've just walked away.

389
00:25:23,963 --> 00:25:25,379
Ignored the problem.

390
00:25:25,380 --> 00:25:28,172
You decided to risk your own safety
to help a stranger.

391
00:25:28,963 --> 00:25:30,463
Wasn't the first time, was it?

392
00:25:33,130 --> 00:25:35,254
- Uh, I don't understand.
- [Matt] Well, I'm just saying

393
00:25:35,255 --> 00:25:37,754
that you've put yourself
in harm's way before. Many times.

394
00:25:37,755 --> 00:25:39,672
The question is why?

395
00:25:40,380 --> 00:25:41,421
Because he was in trouble.

396
00:25:41,422 --> 00:25:43,671
[Matt] You intervened that night
'cause you're a hero.

397
00:25:43,672 --> 00:25:44,754
Matt, don't do this.

398
00:25:44,755 --> 00:25:46,171
Matt, don't do it.

399
00:25:46,172 --> 00:25:48,962
Mr. Ayala, yes or no. Are you
the vigilante known as the White Tiger?

400
00:25:48,963 --> 00:25:50,462
- Objection, Your Honor!
- Order!

401
00:25:50,463 --> 00:25:52,337
- Yes or no? Mr. Ayala?
- [Judge Cooper] Order!

402
00:25:52,338 --> 00:25:54,005
[gavel banging]

403
00:25:54,755 --> 00:25:56,755
Order in my court!

404
00:25:57,797 --> 00:25:59,338
[chorus vocalizing]

405
00:26:00,547 --> 00:26:02,797
Both of you, in my Chambers, now.

406
00:26:11,838 --> 00:26:14,629
Boy, you are a real slippery
piece of shit, you know that?

407
00:26:14,630 --> 00:26:17,254
You sat in that very spot,
and you misled me.

408
00:26:17,255 --> 00:26:19,087
You made representations to me,

409
00:26:19,088 --> 00:26:21,087
you conned me
into suppressing this information,

410
00:26:21,088 --> 00:26:24,004
you lectured me
about what's right and wrong,

411
00:26:24,005 --> 00:26:27,337
and then, you have the nerve to stand up
and make a mockery of my courtroom?

412
00:26:27,338 --> 00:26:28,754
That wasn't my intention, Your Honor.

413
00:26:28,755 --> 00:26:31,087
They somehow got to my star witness.
My hand was forced.

414
00:26:31,088 --> 00:26:34,254
What happened to all that lofty rhetoric
about "unfairly biasing the jury?"

415
00:26:34,255 --> 00:26:36,129
[Matt] Hector's alter ego
is critical to this case.

416
00:26:36,130 --> 00:26:38,421
What he's done as the White Tiger
speaks to the strength of his character.

417
00:26:38,422 --> 00:26:39,921
- My God.
- It's well within my rights--

418
00:26:39,922 --> 00:26:42,254
Is there a Division of Hypocrisy
at Murdock and Associates?

419
00:26:42,255 --> 00:26:43,588
All right, stop it, both of you! Stop it.

420
00:26:45,130 --> 00:26:48,422
[sighs] I can strike this from the record,
but that is pointless.

421
00:26:49,213 --> 00:26:50,671
I can declare a mistrial,

422
00:26:50,672 --> 00:26:53,047
but it's out already,
so I'd say that ship has sailed.

423
00:26:54,880 --> 00:26:56,337
Put me in quite a bind, Mr. Murdock.

424
00:26:56,338 --> 00:26:58,254
I didn't mean to disrespect the court,
Your Honor.

425
00:26:58,255 --> 00:26:59,422
Let me be clear.

426
00:27:00,297 --> 00:27:02,754
You blew open this door, Mr. Murdock.
Which means--

427
00:27:02,755 --> 00:27:05,629
Yeah. It's open season on my client.
I get it.

428
00:27:05,630 --> 00:27:07,130
Well, that's it.

429
00:27:08,130 --> 00:27:09,254
Thank you, Your Honor.

430
00:27:09,255 --> 00:27:10,838
[Hochberg sniffles, clears throat] Um...

431
00:27:11,797 --> 00:27:14,296
Just... I sit atop a pyramid

432
00:27:14,297 --> 00:27:16,337
- of over 500 ADAs.
- Mm.

433
00:27:16,338 --> 00:27:18,462
You're not gonna be able
to stumble into traffic court

434
00:27:18,463 --> 00:27:20,296
without one of them up your ass.

435
00:27:20,297 --> 00:27:21,630
I hope it was worth it.

436
00:27:23,047 --> 00:27:26,587
{\an8}[man] <i>I don't think that
Mr. Ayala is gonna get a fair trial.</i>

437
00:27:26,588 --> 00:27:29,087
{\an8}You know why? He's Puerto Rican.

438
00:27:29,088 --> 00:27:30,671
{\an8}He's gonna single him out.

439
00:27:30,672 --> 00:27:34,379
{\an8}<i>If you have enough evidence,
he should go to prison,</i>

440
00:27:34,380 --> 00:27:37,672
{\an8}but give him a fair trial,
which I don't think he's gonna get it.

441
00:27:39,547 --> 00:27:41,547
[♪ tense music playing]

442
00:27:46,713 --> 00:27:48,130
You should've asked me first.

443
00:27:50,672 --> 00:27:51,672
[Matt] I know.

444
00:27:54,338 --> 00:27:55,880
It wasn't your secret to tell.

445
00:27:58,880 --> 00:28:01,172
Just trying to keep you
outta prison, buddy.

446
00:28:01,755 --> 00:28:04,005
We were losing,
and I had to take a big swing.

447
00:28:08,422 --> 00:28:11,005
You know, Hector, if you are acquitted,

448
00:28:12,172 --> 00:28:13,880
your White Tiger days are over.

449
00:28:15,297 --> 00:28:19,797
I mean, you know that, right?
You can't... ever put that suit back on.

450
00:28:20,463 --> 00:28:22,337
[♪ pensive music playing]

451
00:28:22,338 --> 00:28:23,838
I don't think you understand.

452
00:28:24,880 --> 00:28:28,547
Being the White Tiger
is more than just putting on a suit.

453
00:28:30,172 --> 00:28:31,338
It's who I am.

454
00:28:32,838 --> 00:28:33,963
[chuckles softly]

455
00:28:34,755 --> 00:28:35,755
It's a calling.

456
00:28:37,380 --> 00:28:40,797
I didn't choose it. It chose me.

457
00:28:41,838 --> 00:28:44,004
Might as well ask me to stop breathing.

458
00:28:44,005 --> 00:28:45,213
[Matt chuckles softly]

459
00:28:46,380 --> 00:28:47,880
There are other ways to help.

460
00:28:49,130 --> 00:28:50,463
Other ways to contribute.

461
00:28:52,088 --> 00:28:53,963
Ways that don't require a mask.

462
00:28:54,797 --> 00:28:57,672
You have to think about your family now.
They need you.

463
00:28:58,588 --> 00:28:59,629
And for what it's worth,

464
00:28:59,630 --> 00:29:03,380
I think you might be surprised
at how much you don't miss being him.

465
00:29:09,213 --> 00:29:11,712
[Michael] We had just dropped
our son off at a game.

466
00:29:11,713 --> 00:29:12,880
We were driving home,

467
00:29:13,463 --> 00:29:18,379
and this SUV, it runs a stop sign,
and it just plows right into us.

468
00:29:18,380 --> 00:29:20,255
The engine caught on fire.

469
00:29:21,255 --> 00:29:23,797
[voice breaking] I tried to open the door,
but it was stuck.

470
00:29:24,547 --> 00:29:26,255
I thought for sure we were dead.

471
00:29:27,130 --> 00:29:30,046
Until all of a sudden,
I see someone running toward us.

472
00:29:30,047 --> 00:29:31,630
It was White Tiger.

473
00:29:34,797 --> 00:29:36,088
He saved our lives.

474
00:29:37,172 --> 00:29:39,087
[Gianna] A few weeks ago,
I was leaving work.

475
00:29:39,088 --> 00:29:42,255
It was late, and I have to cut through
this alley to get home.

476
00:29:42,880 --> 00:29:46,463
And this guy, he tries to grab me.
I screamed,

477
00:29:47,088 --> 00:29:48,629
but then I saw he had a knife.

478
00:29:48,630 --> 00:29:50,338
I was so scared.

479
00:29:51,297 --> 00:29:55,213
If White Tiger hadn't been there,
I don't know what would've happened.

480
00:29:56,172 --> 00:29:59,629
[Kirsten] And now, let's hear
from a more objective party.

481
00:29:59,630 --> 00:30:03,796
This is a police report
filed by Officer Lucas Barlow.

482
00:30:03,797 --> 00:30:07,087
"On the night of October 2nd,
at 2:38 a.m.,

483
00:30:07,088 --> 00:30:09,629
"I responded
to an attempted burglary call.

484
00:30:09,630 --> 00:30:13,046
"When I arrived,
the suspect was hiding in an alley,

485
00:30:13,047 --> 00:30:17,046
"and before I could draw my weapon,
he attacked me without provocation.

486
00:30:17,047 --> 00:30:21,129
"We fought.
And then, White Tiger appeared.

487
00:30:21,130 --> 00:30:23,546
"He intervened, pulled the suspect off me,

488
00:30:23,547 --> 00:30:26,672
"then helped me
subdue and arrest the suspect."

489
00:30:29,463 --> 00:30:31,130
[Matt] More police reports.

490
00:30:31,797 --> 00:30:35,212
Officer Reyes, Officer Wong,

491
00:30:35,213 --> 00:30:38,630
Officer Morales, Officer Grant...

492
00:30:39,380 --> 00:30:42,587
All of these tell a different version
of the same story,

493
00:30:42,588 --> 00:30:45,672
and it isn't the story of a man
who has a vendetta against the police.

494
00:30:46,797 --> 00:30:49,546
In fact, I think many of the people
in this room

495
00:30:49,547 --> 00:30:51,713
would consider White Tiger to be an ally.

496
00:30:53,880 --> 00:30:56,088
Mr. Ayala,
let's talk about Mr. and Mrs. Burgos.

497
00:30:56,797 --> 00:31:00,755
Why would you risk your life by running
toward a burning car to save strangers?

498
00:31:01,672 --> 00:31:03,047
It's the right thing to do.

499
00:31:03,672 --> 00:31:05,337
[Matt] What about Gianna Moreno?

500
00:31:05,338 --> 00:31:07,630
You again put yourself in harm's way. Why?

501
00:31:09,797 --> 00:31:11,172
It's the right thing to do.

502
00:31:11,838 --> 00:31:13,754
[Matt] And when you saw
Officer Barlow was in trouble,

503
00:31:13,755 --> 00:31:17,505
you ran in
when others would've run out. Why?

504
00:31:19,963 --> 00:31:21,422
[echoing] It's the right thing to do.

505
00:31:24,630 --> 00:31:27,046
[Matt] The police said
that Hector attacked them,

506
00:31:27,047 --> 00:31:29,713
that he came outta nowhere.
That's what they said.

507
00:31:30,588 --> 00:31:33,672
But why would Hector, the White Tiger...

508
00:31:35,338 --> 00:31:37,796
Why would he do this without the amulet

509
00:31:37,797 --> 00:31:40,505
that gives him
extraordinary strength and power?

510
00:31:41,088 --> 00:31:44,880
Would any of you walk into battle
with one arm tied behind your back?

511
00:31:47,463 --> 00:31:48,588
I wouldn't.

512
00:31:50,838 --> 00:31:54,922
Every night, Hector Ayala
goes out and risks his life

513
00:31:55,838 --> 00:31:59,088
to keep his neighborhood safe,
to protect his community.

514
00:32:00,547 --> 00:32:01,755
So ask yourselves,

515
00:32:02,880 --> 00:32:04,797
does this sound like the type of man

516
00:32:06,047 --> 00:32:08,505
who'd murder a police officer
in cold blood?

517
00:32:09,338 --> 00:32:11,921
He is a man of integrity.

518
00:32:11,922 --> 00:32:13,712
The community says so.

519
00:32:13,713 --> 00:32:16,713
[chuckles] The police say so.

520
00:32:18,422 --> 00:32:21,130
The mask doesn't make the man.

521
00:32:22,130 --> 00:32:25,713
And whether Hector Ayala's wearing
a White Tiger suit or not,

522
00:32:27,463 --> 00:32:28,755
he's a hero.

523
00:32:32,463 --> 00:32:33,588
Thank you.

524
00:32:39,422 --> 00:32:43,754
[Hochberg] You know, every morning,
I get up, I kiss my wife, I call my kids,

525
00:32:43,755 --> 00:32:46,712
I go to work to serve the people
of this great city,

526
00:32:46,713 --> 00:32:48,212
I go to church every Sunday,

527
00:32:48,213 --> 00:32:51,087
I sit in my usual pew,
I give money to my parish,

528
00:32:51,088 --> 00:32:53,546
then I drive out to Queens
to see my mother.

529
00:32:53,547 --> 00:32:56,088
Does that make me a good person?

530
00:32:57,297 --> 00:32:59,004
That was a trick question.

531
00:32:59,005 --> 00:33:01,754
You see, frankly, it's a false premise.

532
00:33:01,755 --> 00:33:04,254
Good people can do bad things.

533
00:33:04,255 --> 00:33:07,004
Bad people can do good things.

534
00:33:07,005 --> 00:33:10,046
Humans... [scoffs] All of us.

535
00:33:10,047 --> 00:33:15,337
We're messy, complicated,
capable of good, capable of evil.

536
00:33:15,338 --> 00:33:19,546
Yes, Hector Ayala
might have done some good things.

537
00:33:19,547 --> 00:33:22,672
Does that make him incapable
of doing a bad thing?

538
00:33:24,963 --> 00:33:26,338
Of course not.

539
00:33:31,922 --> 00:33:35,337
Do you know what happens to a person
when they get hit by a train?

540
00:33:35,338 --> 00:33:39,171
When you have
200,000 pounds of steel slam into you,

541
00:33:39,172 --> 00:33:43,879
all of your bones break,
all of your organs are eviscerated,

542
00:33:43,880 --> 00:33:47,296
your body twists up
like a circus balloon full of blood.

543
00:33:47,297 --> 00:33:50,380
But here's the kicker, you're still alive.

544
00:33:51,713 --> 00:33:54,587
You don't actually die
until they back the train up,

545
00:33:54,588 --> 00:33:57,379
and then your body, it just bursts.

546
00:33:57,380 --> 00:34:00,879
And that is exactly what happened
to Officer Shanahan

547
00:34:00,880 --> 00:34:04,629
when Hector Ayala pushed him
in front of that train.

548
00:34:04,630 --> 00:34:07,296
But we're supposed to be okay
with that, right?

549
00:34:07,297 --> 00:34:10,130
Because he's done
some nice things for people.

550
00:34:11,880 --> 00:34:14,380
Because "it was the right thing to do."

551
00:34:16,797 --> 00:34:17,922
Look around you.

552
00:34:18,630 --> 00:34:23,462
These men and woman you see sitting here,
they're officers of the law.

553
00:34:23,463 --> 00:34:27,504
They took an oath to protect
even in the face of danger.

554
00:34:27,505 --> 00:34:31,712
And every single day,
these brave men and women show up

555
00:34:31,713 --> 00:34:35,254
to serve the people of this city,
to serve you, to serve me,

556
00:34:35,255 --> 00:34:38,838
and they do all that without a mask.

557
00:34:40,963 --> 00:34:45,338
If Hector's sole intent was to do good
for his community, why is he hiding?

558
00:34:46,630 --> 00:34:48,172
Because the last time I checked,

559
00:34:49,630 --> 00:34:51,713
real heroes don't need to hide.

560
00:35:04,755 --> 00:35:06,755
[chorus vocalizing]

561
00:35:47,838 --> 00:35:48,838
[hushed chatter]

562
00:35:50,672 --> 00:35:51,797
Hey.

563
00:35:52,505 --> 00:35:53,547
Hey.

564
00:35:55,297 --> 00:35:56,838
- [Kirsten] You okay?
- [handcuffs clinking]

565
00:36:08,963 --> 00:36:10,504
Has the jury reached a verdict?

566
00:36:10,505 --> 00:36:11,838
We have, Your Honor.

567
00:36:13,297 --> 00:36:14,838
Will the defendant please rise?

568
00:36:19,547 --> 00:36:22,546
In the matter of
the <i>People v. Hector Ayala,</i>

569
00:36:22,547 --> 00:36:25,087
on the count of murder
in the first degree,

570
00:36:25,088 --> 00:36:26,880
the jury finds the defendant...

571
00:36:31,713 --> 00:36:33,338
- not guilty.
- [scattered gasps]

572
00:36:34,338 --> 00:36:36,671
On the count of murder
in the second degree,

573
00:36:36,672 --> 00:36:39,797
the jury finds the defendant not guilty.

574
00:36:41,380 --> 00:36:44,212
On the count of manslaughter
in the first degree,

575
00:36:44,213 --> 00:36:47,129
the jury finds the defendant not guilty.

576
00:36:47,130 --> 00:36:48,297
[indistinct chatter]

577
00:36:50,463 --> 00:36:51,922
[Judge Cooper] This matter is concluded.

578
00:36:52,922 --> 00:36:54,922
[chorus vocalizing]

579
00:36:56,797 --> 00:36:58,297
[Matt] Congratulations, buddy.

580
00:36:59,297 --> 00:37:02,172
[Judge Cooper] Mr. Ayala,
you're free to go.

581
00:37:03,088 --> 00:37:04,380
Thank you, Your Honor. Thank you.

582
00:37:05,130 --> 00:37:06,130
[exclaims]

583
00:37:08,005 --> 00:37:10,088
- [softly] Thanks.
- [Matt] Congratulations, Hector.

584
00:37:13,838 --> 00:37:16,171
- [cameras clicking]
- [Matt] Thank you, all. Thank you.

585
00:37:16,172 --> 00:37:18,254
[reporter] Mr. Murdock,
how do you respond to Mayor Fisk

586
00:37:18,255 --> 00:37:20,004
calling you
and all vigilantes cop killers?

587
00:37:20,005 --> 00:37:22,337
We're grateful
that justice was served, everyone.

588
00:37:22,338 --> 00:37:25,088
{\an8}There's no further comment at this stage.
Thank you.

589
00:37:29,505 --> 00:37:31,505
[♪ uneasy music playing]

590
00:37:34,630 --> 00:37:35,796
Daniel.

591
00:37:35,797 --> 00:37:36,880
Yes, sir.

592
00:37:37,422 --> 00:37:39,379
Your friend, the journalist, BB...

593
00:37:39,380 --> 00:37:42,504
All due respect, sir,
we have people at the <i>Times.</i>

594
00:37:42,505 --> 00:37:44,088
Tell her I wanna see her again.

595
00:37:45,047 --> 00:37:46,255
Absolutely.

596
00:37:56,630 --> 00:37:58,130
[Heather] Gotta love a man who cooks.

597
00:37:58,797 --> 00:38:01,129
And dinner for one in public
is a bit depressing.

598
00:38:01,130 --> 00:38:03,380
[chuckles] Tell me about it.

599
00:38:04,338 --> 00:38:07,254
So, is this the Matt Murdock victory lap?

600
00:38:07,255 --> 00:38:10,837
You win the Ayala case,
and now you get to enjoy the spoils?

601
00:38:10,838 --> 00:38:13,463
Not quite yet. One thing's missing.

602
00:38:14,505 --> 00:38:17,046
You see, my old partner and I,

603
00:38:17,047 --> 00:38:19,546
straight out of law school,
we were so broke,

604
00:38:19,547 --> 00:38:23,922
we pooled about everything we had together
for an office bottle of O'Melveny's.

605
00:38:25,463 --> 00:38:27,922
- [Heather chuckles]
- Only broke it open when we won.

606
00:38:28,547 --> 00:38:31,421
Needless to say, the first bottle lasted
a very long time.

607
00:38:31,422 --> 00:38:33,047
[both chuckle]

608
00:38:34,880 --> 00:38:37,088
Just a nice little reminder that...

609
00:38:38,255 --> 00:38:41,130
once in a while, the system works.

610
00:38:44,588 --> 00:38:48,255
You're talking about your friend,
Foggy Nelson, right?

611
00:38:52,005 --> 00:38:53,088
Yeah.

612
00:38:54,713 --> 00:38:56,213
I was kinda wondering when you would.

613
00:38:59,297 --> 00:39:00,838
It's not easy.

614
00:39:01,797 --> 00:39:05,713
He certainly knew how to enjoy
the good moments when they came.

615
00:39:08,880 --> 00:39:10,088
Well then,

616
00:39:11,922 --> 00:39:13,713
here's to a man who cooks,

617
00:39:15,797 --> 00:39:16,963
a well-won case,

618
00:39:17,505 --> 00:39:20,297
and Foggy Nelson.

619
00:39:22,255 --> 00:39:24,880
May God hold them all
in the hollow of his hand.

620
00:39:26,130 --> 00:39:27,172
[glasses clink]

621
00:39:34,297 --> 00:39:38,505
[Fisk] The Ayala verdict
is an absolute miscarriage of justice.

622
00:39:39,422 --> 00:39:42,629
Well, sir, a court and a jury
found him not guilty.

623
00:39:42,630 --> 00:39:47,047
Courts fail. Juries get it wrong.
I should know.

624
00:39:50,422 --> 00:39:53,837
And now, a masked vigilante,

625
00:39:53,838 --> 00:39:57,047
a murderer,
is allowed to roam the streets,

626
00:39:58,172 --> 00:40:01,880
and a veteran of the NYPD lies dead.

627
00:40:06,380 --> 00:40:08,213
["Una Palabra" by Carlos Valera playing]

628
00:40:17,255 --> 00:40:20,171
[Fisk] <i>These vigilantes are a threat</i>

629
00:40:20,172 --> 00:40:25,630
<i>to any society
that's based on the rule of law.</i>

630
00:40:29,338 --> 00:40:33,172
<i>A man who wears a mask
to cover his face...</i>

631
00:40:35,505 --> 00:40:36,672
<i>is a coward.</i>

632
00:40:41,255 --> 00:40:43,963
These vigilantes, they are not heroes.

633
00:40:47,713 --> 00:40:49,922
[woman screams]

634
00:40:52,297 --> 00:40:53,880
And I ran on a promise,

635
00:40:55,255 --> 00:40:59,880
<i>and the acquittal of Hector Ayala
demands that I keep it.</i>

636
00:41:01,047 --> 00:41:03,088
- [gun fires]
- [bullet casing clatters]

637
00:41:09,422 --> 00:41:11,047
The rule of law must prevail.

638
00:41:30,130 --> 00:41:32,130
[coqui whistling]

639
00:41:33,047 --> 00:41:34,296
[water sloshing]

640
00:41:34,297 --> 00:41:36,088
[waves lapping]

641
00:41:59,130 --> 00:42:01,130
[♪ melancholy music playing]

